 | the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Baseball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Baseball at the 2000 Summer Olympics|Team competition]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Pan American Games]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1999 Pan American Games|1999 Winnipeg]] | [[Baseball at the 1999 Pan American Games|Team competition]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Michael Robert Neill''' (born April 27, 1970 in [[Martinsville, Virginia]]) is a former [[Major League Baseball]] and [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] baseball player. His baseball career included a stint with the [[Oakland Athletics]] and ended with the [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] Gold Medal team in the [[2000 Olympics|2000 games]] in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]].  He was named Delaware Athlete of the Year in 2000.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}  At [[Villanova University]] he compiled a .417 career batting average, led the Wildcats to the 1989 and 1991 Big East Conference crowns and was named 1991 Big East Player of the Year.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}} He established team records: 232 hits, 53 doubles and 379 total bases and several single season records.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\nNeill won two [[Minor League Baseball|Minor League]] batting championships and had a .307 batting average over 11 years.  He was selected to 4 All-Star teams and was a key player in the [[Vancouver Canadians]]' 1999 AAA World Series victory.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}  He was called up by the [[Oakland Athletics]] in {{baseball year|1998}} but was sidelined with an injury.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}} Neill led the 2000 USA Olympics team to a 4-0 win over Cuba in the gold medal game with a 1st-inning home run and a dramatic sliding catch in the 9th inning.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}  His walk off homer against Japan won the team's 1st round Olympic contest.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}  During the [[1999 Pan American Games]] he had the game-winning hit to clinch the Olympic berth for his USA team.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\nNeill has spent the past 6 years as a financial adviser, currently with [[Morgan Stanley Smith Barney]] in [[Philadelphia]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}  In 2005, he was inducted into the [[Delaware]] Hall of Fame.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}  And in 2007, he was inducted into the [[Villanova University|Villanova]] Hall of Fame.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\nNeil currently resides in [[Radnor, Pennsylvania]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1991 College Baseball All-America Team]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Baseballstats | br=n/neillmi01 }}\n* [http://www.baseball-almanac.com/players/player.php?p=neillmi01 Baseball Almanac]\n* {{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ne/mike-neill-1.html}}\n\n{{Big East Conference Baseball Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{2000 Olympic Champions Baseball}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Neill, Mike}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college baseball players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Edmonton Trappers players]]\n[[Category:Huntsville Stars players]]\n[[Category:Modesto A's players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Olympic baseball players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for the United States in baseball]]\n[[Category:Pawtucket Red Sox players]]\n[[Category:Reno Silver Sox players]]\n[[Category:Southern Oregon A's players]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Rainiers players]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Tigers players]]\n[[Category:Vancouver Canadians players]]\n[[Category:Villanova Wildcats baseball players]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 1999 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:People from Martinsville, Virgin